IPv6 PIM-SM (Sparse Mode) Example
=================================

This is the pure-IPv6 counterpart of the IPv4 PIM-SM example (see ../sm),
demonstrating the rendezvous-point machinery over IPv6: Register /
Register-Stop, the shared (*,G) tree, and the switchover to the (S,G) source
tree. It uses MulticastRouter6 nodes running PIM in sparse mode, with
Ipv6FlatNetworkConfigurator for addressing and MLD for group membership.

The three routers form a triangle so that the shortest path from the receiver
side to the source does NOT go through the RP:

    Source --- DR_S ===== RP
                 \\       //
                  \\     //
                   == DR_R --- Receiver

DR_S is the source's designated router, RP is the (statically configured)
rendezvous point at aaaa:1:65:0:8aa:ff:fe00:4, and DR_R is the receiver's
designated router. The Receiver joins group ff0e::8 before the source starts,
so the shared (*,G) tree toward the RP is built first. When the Source starts
sending (t=20s), DR_S encapsulates the traffic in PIM Register messages to the
RP; the RP forwards it down the shared tree to the Receiver and joins the
source tree. The last-hop router DR_R then switches to the shortest-path tree,
joining (S,G) toward the Source over the direct DR_S--DR_R link (bypassing the
RP).

Duplicate Address Detection is disabled (dupAddrDetectTransmits = 0) for a
fast, deterministic startup.

To run the example:

    inet -u Cmdenv -c General
